 three upright stones capped with a headstone (from Old English <i>fe(o)ther-</i> ‘four’ + <i>stān</i> ‘stone’)."],"variants":[{"name":"Featherston","meanings":["English: variant of   Featherstone  ."]},{"name":"Featherson","meanings":["English: variant of   Featherstone   with loss of <i>-t-</i>."]},{"name":"Fetherston","meanings":["English: variant of   Featherstone  ."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: possibly a metonymic occupational name for a fisherman, from <i>orfe</i>, a species of freshwater fish. Alternatively, a habitational name from Urff near Kassel, formerly Orpha."],"variants":[{"name":"Orff","meanings":["German: variant of   Orf  ."]}]},{"name":"Featherstonehaugh","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Featherstonhaugh  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Featherstonhaugh","meanings":["English: locative name from Featherstone in Haltwhistle (Northumb), recorded earlier as  <i>Fetherstanhalcht</i> about 1215.  Compare  Featherstone  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":80,"year":"1215","julia